### Understanding the Metrics
- **Spectral Convergence (SC)**: Measures magnitude similarity in the frequency domain. Low scores mean frequency content is distorted or "smeared".
- **Log Spectral Distance (LSD)**: Measures spectral difference in dB. High values indicate tonal coloration or gain issues. This is the largest contributor to the remaining gap — improving LSD has the highest leverage.
- **MFCC Distance**: Measures timbral similarity. High distance means the "character" of the sound has changed.
- **Transient Preservation (TP)**: Measures how well onsets (drum hits, etc.) are preserved. Low scores mean transients are "softened" or "doubled".
- **Stereo Width (SWP)**: Mid/side energy ratio preservation. Low scores mean the stereo image collapsed or widened relative to the reference.
- **Interchannel Correlation (ICC)**: L-R phase relationship preservation. Low scores mean stereo decorrelation has changed.
- **Panning Consistency (PP)**: Frame-by-frame L-R balance curve correlation. Low scores mean panning shifts have been introduced.

### Strategy Guidance
- **LSD is ~79% of the remaining gap** — prioritize spectral distance reduction over other metrics.
- Parameter-level tweaks at score 84+ have only a ~13% success rate. Consider **architectural changes**: different PV implementations, overlap-save vs overlap-add, multi-resolution analysis.
- For stereo cases: mid/side processing in `src/stretch/hybrid.rs` is the key code path. Stereo metrics (SWP, ICC, PP) measure how well the L-R relationship is preserved through stretching.
